  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish: this is usually the English name, especially in Ulster, but elsewhere in Ireland it was also adopted for the Gaelic topographic byname, <b>an Mhuilinn</b> ‘of the mill’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":34,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Mylles was born about 1348, in Harescombe, Gloucestershire, England as the son of Thomas Myll. He married Juliana le Rous about 1390. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died on 11 June 1422, in his hometown, at the age of 75, and was buried in Harescombe, Gloucestershire, England."},"et":{"about 1348–11 June 1422":"umbes 1348–11. juuni 1422","1348–1422":"1348–1422","1358–1422":"1358–1422","1394–Male":"1394–Surnud","1398–Female":"1398–Surnud","1400–1470":"1400–1470","1330–1395":"1330–1395","11 June 1422":"11. juuni 1422","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1394":"1394","20 June 1422":"20. juuni 1422","1382":"1382","1470":"1470","1348":"1348","1358":"1358","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","Abt 1398":"umbes 1398","1398"